2 to power 5 = 32, total 32 ip I will get like 172.126.10.0  - 172.126.10.31
The reason: Binary structure of IP addresses
This is a really insightful question! You're asking why IP address ranges always come in powers of 2, like 2Â¹, 2Â², 2âµ, 2Â¹â¶ â€” but never 2â¹ or 2Â¹Â¹ usable addresses, for example. Let's break it down.
1.	IP addresses are built in binary.
o	IPv4 addresses are 32 bits long.
o	Every bit can have 2 possible values: 0 or 1.
o	So, the number of possible addresses is always some power of 2.


Parameter                              | Formula / Rule                 | Example (172.198.10.0/27)
--------------------------------   ----|------------------------------ -|------------------------------
Total IPs                              | 2^(32 - CIDR)                  | 2^(32-27) = 32
Usable IPs                             | 2^(32 - CIDR) - 2              | 32 - 2 = 30 usable
Network IP                             | First IP of the block          | 172.198.10.0
Broadcast IP                           | Network IP + Total IPs - 1     | 172.198.10.0 + 32 - 1 = 172.198.10.31
Subnet increment / Next subnet start   | Network IP + Total IPs         | 172.198.10.0 + 32 = 172.198.10.32
Host bits                              | 32 - CIDR                      | 32 - 27 = 5 bits for hosts
Valid subnet alignment                 | Starting octet must be multiple of block size in that octet | 32 IPs â†’ third octet multiples of 2: 0,2,4,6,8,10â€¦


ğŸŒ OSI models (open system interconnection)	
----------------------------------------------------------

The OSI model (Open Systems Interconnection model) is a conceptual framework that standardizes how different computer systems communicate over a network.
It divides the communication process into 7 layers, each with specific roles â€” from sending physical signals to displaying the final data to a user.

OSI HAS 7 LAYERS (APSTNDP in short):
1>> layer 7 >>  Application (http, https)
2>> layer 6 >> presentation (syntax, security & encryption)
3>> layer 5 >> session (API, Socket)
4>> layer 4 >> Transport (TCP)
5>> layer 3 >> Networks(packets)
6>> layer 2 >> Data link(ethernet)
7>> layer 1 >> Physical ()

##  the first 3 layers are called software layers,  the last 3 layers are called the hardware layers and the middle one (transport layer) is it handles the data communication between the software and hardware layers .
Understand like 
(7) Application â€“ You write the letter
(6) Presentation â€“ Translate it
(5) Session â€“ Organize the conversation
(4) Transport â€“ Deliver in correct order
(3) Network â€“ Choose best route
(2) Data Link â€“ Deliver to correct device
(1) Physical â€“ Wires, Wi-Fi, actual delivery


COOMUNICATION PROTOCOLS: 
----------------------------
A communication protocol is like a set of rules that computers follow to talk to each other.
It decides how data is sent, received, and understood between two devices â€” like your phone and a website, or two servers.

| Protocol               | What it Does                                      |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| **HTTP / HTTPS**       | How web browsers talk to websites                 |
| **WebSocket**          | How live chats and games send instant messages    |
| **FTP / SFTP**         | How files are moved between computers             |
| **SMTP / IMAP / POP3** | How emails are sent and received                  |
| **SSH**                | How to securely control another computer remotely |
| **MQTT / CoAP**        | How small smart devices (IoT) send data           |

ğŸŒ 1. HTTP â€” HyperText Transfer Protocol
The main language of the web.
Itâ€™s how your browser asks a website for pages, images, or data.
Example: when you visit google.com, your browser says â€œHey server, give me the homepage,â€ and the server sends it back.
ğŸ§­ Think of it like sending a letter and getting a reply.

ğŸ”’ 2. HTTPS â€” HTTP Secure
